"https://news.google.com/rss/search?q=us+national+news+site:cnn.com","Live updates: Protests against Trump ICE raids flare across US","https://www.cnn.com/us/live-news/la-protests-ice-raids-trump-06-12-25","Thu, 12 Jun 2025 16:11:00 GMT","

Live Updates


• Protests spread: Demonstrations against ICE raids and President Donald Trump's mobilization of troops in Los Angeles have served as flashpoints for immigration unrest across the country, with protests springing up in New York, Seattle, Chicago, Austin, Las Vegas and Washington, DC.
    


• Ready to deploy: The military says 700 US Marines have completed training and will be deployed in LA in the next two days. Meanwhile, a hearing is scheduled today on California's push to limit how the Trump administration can use the Marines and National Guard in the state.
    


• “No Kings” rallies: More than 1,800 protests and events denouncing what organizers describe as authoritarian actions by the Trump administration are planned nationwide Saturday — the same day Trump is holding a military parade in Washington, DC. Preparations are underway across the country, including in San Antonio, Texas, where Gov. Greg Abbott says the state's National Guard could be deployed.
    


            The Trump administration filed another lawsuit against New York's sanctuary policies Thursday, alleging that a state law banning undocumented immigrants from being arrested at a courthouse blocks federal immigration agents from doing their job.
    


            The law, called the Protect Our Courts Act, was implemented in 2020 and imposes a criminal penalty on anyone who arrests undocumented people at, or on their way to and from, any court hearing.
    


            The lawsuit is another step in a crackdown by the Trump administration on sanctuary cities.
    


                    “Lawless sanctuary city policies are the root cause of the violence that Americans have seen in California, and New York State is similarly employing sanctuary city policies to prevent illegal aliens from apprehension,” Attorney General Pam Bondi said in a statement Thursday.
                





            Arresting someone at or near a courthouse, “often reduces the risk of flight and safety risks to the public, law enforcement officers, and targets themselves, in part because individuals are usually screened for weapons or other contraband before entering a courthouse,” according to the lawsuit.
    


            The Protect our Courts Act poses “intolerable obstacles to federal immigration enforcement,” the lawsuit reads, because it “facilitates the evasion of federal law by dangerous criminals.”
    


                    “Immigrants make New York great,” a spokesperson for the New York state attorney general's office said in a statement. “The Protect Our Courts Act ensures every New Yorker can access our courts and pursue justice without fear, because due process means nothing if people are too afraid to appear in court.”
                





            The Justice Department has filed several other suits challenging cities with sanctuary policies, including a challenge to New York City, four cities in New Jersey, and Chicago.
    


            The Los Angeles Police Department made more than 80 arrests amid anti-ICE protests and criminal activity in the downtown Los Angeles area on Wednesday, according to an update from the department.
    


            There were 71 arrests for failure to disperse; seven arrests for curfew violations; two arrests for assault with a deadly weapon on a police officer; and one arrest for resisting a police officer, the department said.
    


            Law enforcement used “numerous less-lethal munitions,” during the crowd control situation Wednesday, according to police.
    


            Defense Secretary Pete Hegseth declined to say whether he would abide by a federal court order if the court decides to block the Trump administration from using the federalized National Guard and Marines to help with immigration enforcement in California.
    


            A federal judge will hold a hearing on Thursday over California's request to bar the administration from using the troops.
    


            “Whatever the federal district court decides, will you abide by it?”  Democratic Rep. Ro Khanna of California asked.
    


                    “Well, this is a pending situation,” Hegseth said. “My job right now is to ensure that the troops that we have in Los Angeles are capable of supporting law enforcement there.”
                





            When asked again if he would abide by the decisions of the courts, Hegseth said, “We've always looked at the decisions of the courts.”
    


            Khanna again asked Hegseth if he can “assure the American people” that he “will respect any Supreme Court decision on this matter – about whether the Marines are constitutional – and you will respect the district courts when they rule before the Supreme Court rules?”
    


            Hegseth again demurred, responding that judges should not be determining foreign policy or national security. “What I can say is we should not have local judges determining foreign policy or national security policy for the country,” Hegseth said.
    


            Texas Governor Greg Abbott on Thursday deployed over 2,000 Texas Department of Public Safety troopers and over 5,000 Texas National Guard soldiers across the state “to assist local law enforcement response” to anti-ICE protests and “to maintain law and order,” according to a news release from the governor's office.
    


            “Peaceful protests are part of the fabric of our nation, but Texas will not tolerate the lawlessness we have seen in Los Angeles in response to President Donald Trump's enforcement of immigration law,” Abbott said. “Anyone engaging in acts of violence or damaging property will be arrested and held accountable to the full extent of the law.”
    


            The state has “strategically positioned” more than 5,000 Texas National Guard soldiers to “bolster state and local law enforcement response to any criminal activity,” and more than 2,000 DPS troopers, including Special Agents and Texas Rangers, are deployed “to respond to potential criminal or violent activity” at the protests, according to the governor.
    


            Democratic governors slammed President Donald Trump's deployment of the National Guard and Marines to California amid protests over the administration's immigration enforcement policies during a hearing on Capitol Hill Thursday.
    


                    “As we speak, an American city has been militarized over the objections of their governor,” New York Gov. Kathy Hochul said as she began her testimony at the hearing. “At the outset I just want to say that this is a flagrant abuse of power and nothing short of an assault on our American values.”
                





            Hochul, Illinois Gov. JB Pritzker and Minnesota Gov. Tim Walz are testifying at a hearing focused on “sanctuary state” policies.
    


Some context: The hearing is playing out against the backdrop of protests in Los Angeles and cities across the country against the Trump administration's immigration enforcement actions. California Gov. Gavin Newsom has clashed with Trump over his decision to deploy National Guard and Marines to Los Angeles despite opposition from the state and city's Democratic leaders.
    


            Walz, who noted his state does not have “sanctuary” legislation guiding enforcement policies, blasted the Trump administration's “cruel and misguided policies.”
    


                    “We have a broken immigration system in this country,” he said. “I think everyone in this room agrees with that. But nothing Minnesota has done to serve its own people stands in the way of the federal government managing border security and policies.”
                





            Each governor laid the blame at Congress' feet for failing to adequately tackle comprehensive immigration reform.
    


            President Donald Trump hinted Thursday that his administration may soon revise some of its immigration policies, in response to growing concerns from farmers and business leaders about labor shortages caused by his aggressive stance on immigration.
    


                    “Our great Farmers and people in the Hotel and Leisure business have been stating that our very aggressive policy on immigration is taking very good, long-time workers away from them, with those jobs being almost impossible to replace,” Trump wrote in a social media post. “In many cases the Criminals allowed into our Country by the VERY Stupid Biden Open Borders Policy are applying for those jobs. This is not good. We must protect our Farmers but get the CRIMINALS OUT OF THE USA. Changes are coming!”
                





            Trump did not provide details on what policy changes may be underway but emphasized that the goal is to support American agriculture and hospitality industries while continuing to target undocumented immigrants with criminal records.
    


            The president's post marks a rare public acknowledgment of the economic strain some sectors say they've faced due to labor shortages in regions that have long relied on immigrant labor.
    


            CNN has reached out to the White House for more information on the potential changes to immigration policies.
    


            The League of United Latin American Citizens issued a national advisory to members, allies, and community stakeholders as protests against Immigration and Customs Enforcement operations have spread across the country.
    


                    “LULAC stands for lawful, nonviolent protest,” said Roman Palomares, LULAC national president and chairman of its board. “Anyone joining a demonstration must understand that an act even perceived as assaulting National Guard soldiers or federal agents is a federal crime that can carry serious prison sentences. We should avoid reckless behavior that overshadows our just cause or endangers our people,” he added.
                





Remember: Immigration agents are expected to get help from National Guard units in Texas. Gov. Greg Abbott said on Wednesday that the state's National Guard was ready to respond if protests emerged there.
    


                    “Texans are watching in grief and disbelief as armored vehicles roll down our streets, treating peaceful neighbors as threats for daring to speak out,” said Gabriel Rosales, the Texas LULAC state director. “Military deployments and tactics aimed at silencing us only deepen the pain of communities already wounded by ICE raids and strip away the First Amendment freedoms our state claims to cherish.”
                





            Three Democratic governors are preparing to defend their state's immigration enforcement policies before the House Oversight and Government Reform Committee on Thursday, a hearing playing out against the backdrop of protests in Los Angeles and other cities over President Donald Trump's immigration policies.
    


            Illinois Gov. JB Pritzker, Minnesota Gov. Tim Walz, and New York Gov. Kathy Hochul will testify at what the committee describes as a “hearing with sanctuary state governors.”
    


                    “Illinois follows federal and state laws and will continue to do so. We expect the federal government to do the same. Federal officials should operate in Illinois, as they do in every state, to enforce federal immigration policy,” Pritzker said in written testimony ahead of the hearing.
                





             “But we will not divert our limited resources and officers to do the job of the federal government when it is not in the best interest of our state, our local communities, or the safety of our residents.”
    


            It comes as the role of Democratic governors has been in the spotlight as California Gov. Gavin Newsom has clashed with Trump over the president's deployment of the National Guard and Marines to Los Angeles.
    


            The high-profile hearing, which includes potential 2028 contenders, has the potential to produce testy exchanges with Republican lawmakers eager to highlight Democratic-led states with “sanctuary” policies – a broad term referring to policies that limit cooperation with federal immigration enforcement actions.
    


            House Democratic Rep. Jimmy Gomez told CNN's Sara Sidner that he believes the federalization of the National Guard and “boots on the ground” in Los Angeles were never about maintaining peace and order.
    


            “It was always about getting more troops on the ground to support his (President Donald Trump's) ICE raids, to enforce immigration law,” Gomez said.
    


            “In the city and county of LA, there's 10 million individuals, 34 percent are foreign born. So he (Trump) says he's going to save us from criminals. Who is he saving us from? Ourselves?” the congressman said.
    


            Gomez reiterated that much of the protest activity remains isolated to a few blocks around a group of federal buildings, noting that his wife and 3-year-old son attendend a prayer vigil against deportation raids downtown and were “completely fine.”
    


            Gomez represents California's 34th Congressional District which includes downtown Los Angeles.
    


            Newly released video from ICE shows the moment Homeland Security Investigations officers detained a man accused of assaulting a US Border Patrol agent.
    


            The Department of Homeland Security identified the man as Christian Damian Cerno-Camacho.
    


            Agents boxed in Cerno-Camacho's vehicle, while his partner and a toddler were inside, at an intersection in Los Angeles' Boyle Heights neighborhood. Agents can then be seen around it with guns drawn.
    


Watch the moment unfold here:



            “Clearly this administration, this government is not following the rule of law it's engaging in terror, violence and acting outside the scope of its authority,” Christian Contreras, attorney for the family, said in a news conference Wednesday afternoon.
    


            Cerno-Camacho also faces charges for allegedly “fleeing to avoid prosecution and damage to federal property after he attempted to flee in his vehicle,” according to a post on X from ICE.
    


            Surveillance video obtained by CNN on Wednesday shows the moment from a different angle.
    


            There was minor damage to the vehicle's right side, where the toddler was sitting in a car seat, video shared with CNN from a local organization showed.
    


            The incident was a “targeted arrest of a violent rioter who punched a CBP officer,” said Department of Homeland Security spokesperson Tricia McLaughlin.
    


            When Homeland Security Investigations tried to take the man into custody for the alleged assault, he tried to flee, she said.
    


CNN's Cindy Von Quednow, Norma Galeana, Kyung Lah, Julianna Bragg and Jillian Sykes contributed to this report



            Protests erupted outside hotels across the Los Angeles County area Wednesday night when  dozens of protesters showed up, some holding signs, according to reporting from CNN affiliate KABC.
    


            Aerial footage from the scene of at least one of the protests, showed a crowd outside a hotel in Whittier, California. The crowd appeared to grow and spread onto the streets surrounding the hotel, prompting a response from police.
    


            The protest is believed to have followed unconfirmed social media reports that US Immigration and Customs Enforcement agents were staying in the building, according to Reuters.
    


            A similar scenario took place Wednesday night at hotels in Pasadena and Downey, where people waved flags and held up signs protesting ICE, KABC reported.
    


            Cities across the United States are bracing for protests against the Trump administration this Saturday - the same day President Donald Trump is holding a military parade in Washington, DC, celebrating the 250th anniversary of the US Army. It will coincide with Trump's 79th birthday.
    


            More than 1,800 so-called “No Kings” rallies and events are planned that day, organized by the 50501 movement under the banner of “a day of defiance.”
    


            The name “50501” means “50 protests, 50 states, 1 movement,” according to the group's website. “No Kings” represents a rejection of the Trump administration's sweeping actions since he took office, which the group believes to be authoritarian.
    


            “The corruption has gone too. far. No thrones. No crowns. No kings,” the 50501 website reads.
    


            “No Kings” states that a core principle behind all its events is “a commitment to nonviolent action” and it expects all participants “to seek to de-escalate any potential confrontation with those who disagree with our values” and to act lawfully. The group says no weapons of any kind, “including those legally permitted,” should be brought to its events.
    


            The parade is expected to be the largest the city has seen in decades, bringing seven million pounds of vehicles and weaponry as well as a price tag potentially in the tens of millions of dollars. In early June, the US Army began reinforcing the roads that will carry the hardware downtown and along the parade route.
    


            The exclusion of Washington, DC of the map of the protests by “No Kings” is deliberate as Trump's military parade takes place in the nation's capital.
    


            “Instead of allowing this birthday parade to be the center of gravity, we will make action everywhere else the story of America that day: people coming together in communities across the country to reject strongman politics and corruption,” its website reads.
    


            Texas Gov. Greg Abbott said earlier this week the state's National Guard will be deployed to various locations ahead of planned protests, including a “No Kings” event in San Antonio on Saturday.
    


            At least three people have been detained in Tucson, Arizona, during an anti-ICE protest, according to CNN affiliate KOLD.
    


            More than 100 people gathered in the city Wednesday, KOLD reported.
    


                    “We're here to protect Tucson. We're here to protect our neighborhoods. We're here to protect our community,” one unnamed protester told KOLD. 
                





            Some protesters vandalized property, including breaking windows and spray painting walls, video from KOLD shows. Four policemen can be seen carrying one protester by their arms and legs, video shows.
    


            Activated US Marines have completed their training and will be deployed to Los Angeles within the next 48 hours, according to the US Northern Command.
    


            About 700 Marines have finished a “pre-deployment workup,” it said late on Wednesday.
    


                    “When called up for this mission, the battalion underwent additional training specific to this mission. This training included de-escalation, crowd-control, and understanding the Standing Rules for the Use of Force (SRUF),” it said. 
                





            These rules govern the use of force by military personnel during missions to support law enforcement inside the US. Northern Command notes the forces themselves “do not conduct civilian law enforcement functions.”
    


            The Marines are bolstering a deployment of about 2,000 National Guard troops currently on active duty and helping ICE agents, and another 2,000 Guard members who will be ready for duty Thursday afternoon, according to Maj. Gen. Scott M. Sherman, who is leading the task force.
    


Happening today: A hearing is scheduled for this afternoon in federal court over whether the Trump administration can use the National Guard and Marines to assist with federal immigration enforcement actions.
    


            Police in Seattle, Washington, have arrested eight protesters after anti-ICE protests flared in the city Wednesday, its police department said in a statement.
    


            Protesters “marched peacefully from Capitol Hill to downtown Seattle as part of a demonstration,” the statement said.
    


            While most of the march was peaceful, officers intervened after some individuals set fire to a dumpster at around 10 p.m. local time, police said.
    


                    “Police staged near the group while they waited for the Seattle Fire Department to arrive. Individuals from the group confronted them, throwing bottles, rocks, and concrete chunks at them,” the statement said. “A protestor threw a large firework at officers, but no one was injured.”
                





            Footage shared with CNN on Wednesday night shows Los Angeles police pulling people out from the crowd of protesters to be detained.
    


            The video, provided by non-profit news organization CalMatters, showed police confronting protesters in and around Koreatown, about 3 miles from the curfew zone that went into effect at 8 p.m. Pacific Time.
    


            It showed officers walking toward a group of protesters, taking hold of one person and escorting them away with their hands held behind their back.
    


            In another video, several officers are seen running toward a different group, shouting: “Get back, get back!” as they detain another individual.
    


            Earlier on Wednesday night, a CNN reporter on the ground witnessed protesters driving through an area where the curfew does not apply — heading in the direction of Koreatown.
    


            Videos shot by CNN show a line of cars honking loudly, with some passengers leaning out the window or standing upright on truck beds waving Mexican and American flags. Some protesters are seen walking on foot.
    


            The curfew currently in place only covers about 1 square mile in area in Downtown Los Angeles where the protests had been concentrated.
    


            Protests have spread beyond Los Angeles, with demonstrations against ICE and the Trump administration popping up in major cities across the United States.
    


            In both LA and Spokane, Washington, city authorities imposed curfews on Wednesday night.  In many other cities, police departments worked to disperse protesters long after night fell.
    


            The curfew in parts of downtown LA lasts from 8 p.m. to 6 a.m. Pacific Time. But the curfew is only in place for a very small strip of the city, measuring about 1 square mile in area.
    


            LA Mayor Karen Bass said the curfew could be in effect for several days.
    


            Things could pick up on Saturday, when there are “No Kings” protests and anti-Trump rallies scheduled across the country. The protests, organized by the nonviolent 50501 movement, come on the same day as President Donald Trump's planned military parade through Washington, DC.
    


            The name of the protests represents a rejection of the Trump administration's sweeping actions since he took power, which the group describes as authoritarian.
    


                    “In America, we don't do kings,” the 50501 movement's website reads. “The corruption has gone too. far. No thrones. No crowns. No kings.”
                





            Protesters took to the streets in cities across the country Wednesday, demonstrating against President Donald Trump's immigration policies and raids by US Immigration and Customs Enforcement.
    


            The protests began on Friday in Los Angeles, where a curfew is in place and where the Trump administration has federalized the National Guard.
    


See more images from the protests in Los Angeles. 



            Hundreds of people gathered in San Antonio, Texas, late Wednesday to protest against raids by Immigration and Customs Enforcement, according to CNN affiliate KSAT.
    


            The protests were peaceful and there were no reports of violence, KSAT reported.
    


                    “I'm here because I want to be a voice for the people that are too scared to come out here and speak their own truth,” one protester told KSAT.
                





            The gathering started before 7 p.m. local time with a crowd of about 100 people, before swelling to hundreds by about 9 p.m., according to KSAT.
    


            Texas' governor deployed the Texas National Guard to San Antonio ahead of the protests.
    


            San Antonio Police Chief William McManus said Wednesday that officers would intervene if “it turns violent,” KSAT reported.
    


            Troops with the Texas Department of Public Safety were seen patrolling the area as San Antonio police officers drove through downtown, according to KSAT.
    


            Firefighters in Seattle extinguished a dumpster fire that was set on the road and police were still working to disperse protesters just before midnight, according to the city's police department.
    


            Videos shot on Wednesday night showed a large crowd on the streets and a fire burning at an intersection. At points, protesters threw items into the fire, including a traffic cone.
    


            The fire department “has extinguished the dumpster fire. Police are attempting to get crowd to disperse,” the police department wrote on X.
    


                    “Officers continue moving the groups away from the federal building. Individuals are shining lasers at officers as well as throwing rocks and bottles at them. We will continue to move protestors until the individuals stop assaulting officers,” it wrote.
                




